As a math person, I'd highly suggest reading up on optimal stopping problems! It's exactly what you saw in my example.

Postscript

You might be saying, this isn't very Bayesian. Nor is it very Bayesian at all. But I think it forces you to engage with Bayesian ideas in a more native way that aligns better with real life. Let me know if you have any questions! As always, pushback is welcome‚Äîthis is just a warmup exercise. :)

Does this belong in hackingML, contemporary ML, entertainment? More and more generally, where does this belong? I'm not sure. In any case, I wanted to share it with everyone!
